            <h1>Chile!</h1> 
        </header>
        <main>
            <p> 
                From the driest desert in the world up north to eternal glaciers and 
                inverted waterfalls down south, Chile extends travellers an invitation 
                that is hard to turn down. Situated along the western seaboard of South America, 
                Chile extends from its boundary with Peru, to the tip of South America at Cape Horn, 
                only about 400 miles north of Antarctica. Boasting one of the more urbanised Latin American societies,
                and a democratic government, you can feel truly safe whilst getting to grips with its diverse people 
                and geography!  
            </p>
            <h2> What to see:</h2>
            <p> Here are the top five places to visit in Chile:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Santiago - The Capital. Surrounded by the Andes mountains, 
                    Santiago has to be one of the most beautiful capital cities on the planet. 
                    It’s also a very fun place to visit, with a rich history, vibrant culture, and great tourism infrastructure.</li>
                <li>Rapa Nui - AKA - Easter island. Discover the mysterious culture of the Rapa Nui people and the iconic moai statues.
                    While most people visit Rapa Nui to explore its cultural history the island is also home to some excellent diving, 
                    surfing, and enticing beaches when a bit of relaxation is in order</li>
                <li>San Pedro De Atacama - an age-old town with dirt roads and adobe homes. Here you can explore the arts and crafts centre of Chile
                     by day and by night gaze at the endless amounts of stars twinkling across the sky of the driest desert in the world. </li>
                <li>Torres del Paine National Park - a vast national park not far from Patagonia. The jaw-dropping landscapes of this eighth wonder of the world could keep you busy for months! 
                    At this national park you can sail on Lake Grey to admire the eponymous glacier, or paddle a kayak through its colossal blue and white icebergs.</li>  
                <li>Chiloé- an extraordinary island full of myths and legends, unique folklore and culinary traditions. Made famous by its quaint palafitos – colourful houses built on stilts above the water, 
                    and the island’s striking landscapes. Visiting Chiloé is like entering a magical world blessed in nature and culture. From the moment you first set foot on this extraordinary island, 
                    its singular identity will take you by surprise.</li> 
            </ol>
            <div class="row">
