            <h2> Food:</h2>
        <p>When you're tired from a long day seeing the sights, why not try some delicious local cuisine? Here are some top dishes to seek out whilst in Chile. </p>
        <ol>
            <li>Pastel de choclo (corn-based dish)</li>
            <li>Empanadas de pino</li>
            <li>Curanto en hoyo (Clambake) from Chiloé - food is steamed in a hole covered with native leaves and cooked over hot stones.</li>
            <li>Arrollado huaso (Pork roll peasant style)</li>
            <li>Longanizas de Chillán</li>
        </ol>
        <a href="url"> Please click here for some unbeatable chilean restaurants and cafes! </a>
        <p><img src="la-vega-market-santiago-pablo-rogat-shutterstock.jpg" width="420" height="315"> </p>

        <h2>Transport:</h2>
        <p>It is relatively easy to travel around Chile. Buses are now the main means of long distance transportation in Chile, 
            following the decline of the rail network. The bus system covers the whole country, from Arica to Santiago 
            (a 30-hour journey) and from Santiago to Punta Arenas (about 40 hours, with a change at Osorno).  </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Buses:  Chile's biggest bus company is TurBus, with an all-embracing network of services around the country. There is also Pullman.</li>
                <li>Cars: Automóvil Club de Chile (rentals) </li>
                <li>Planes: Chile has several domestic airlines. LATAM has the most routes. Sky Airlines, LAW and JetSmart are other options.</li>
            </ul>
            <img src="Valparaiso-1024x768.jpg" width="420" height="315"> 

            <h2>Where To Stay:</h2>
            <p>
                Chile boasts troves of fantastic places to stay, whether in the grand metropolis of Santiago, or in shadow of the andes.
                 The majority of these are safe and friendly. The costs of rooms depends on the type of hotel or hostel and what extra features you would like, 
                 including how much privacy you’re hoping for.</p>
             <a href="url"> Please click here for a full breakdown of the different places to stay according to various cities and prices! </a>
             <p>
             <img src="argentina-and-chile-amazing-patagonia-13-days-tour-2-480470_1564689932.JPG" width="420" height="315"> 
            </p>
            <h2>Language Tips:</h2>
            <p>Spanish is the official language and it spoken by all Chileans. There are, however, other languages or dialects still used by indigenous communities of the country. 
                Spanish was inherited from the Spanish Conquistadores, but throughout the years phonetic, syntactic, and lexical traits have allowed a new Chilean Spanish to develop. 
            </p>
           <h3>Some Spanish phrases:</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>¡Hola! – Hello </li>
                <li>¿Cómo estás? – How are you? </li>
                <li>Por favor – please </li>
                <li>Gracias – thank you </li>
                <li>¿Dónde está la calle [de Alcalá]? – Where is [Alcalá] Street? </li>
                <li> Estoy perdido – I’m lost </li>
                <li>¿Dónde puedo encontrar un taxi?– Where can I get a taxi? </li>
                <li>¿Cuánto cuesta? – How much is it? </li>
                <li>La cuenta, por favor – The bill, please. </li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Some "Chilean-isms":</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>¿Cachai? – you know?/you got it? </li>
                <li>Po – used after si and no</li>
                <li>Taco – a traffic jam</li>
                <li>¿Qué onda? – how’s it going? </li>
                <li>Al tiro – right now</li>
            </ul>
            <img src="cover-for-Places-To-Visit-In-Chile_10th-dec.jpg" width="420" height="315"> 

            <h2>Safety tips:</h2>
            <p>According to the Safe Cities Index, recently prepared by The Economist, Santiago is the safest city in Latin America. 
                Meanwhile, a worldwide study prepared by Newsweek rates Chile as the best country in Latin America to live.
                When visiting, it is important to look after your bags/suitcases to avoid theft.
                Make sure to carry copies of all your important documents, including the address of where you are staying. 
                Make sure to stay with people during the evenings, and avoid walking home alone at night. 
                Chile is a land of extreme natural events: volcanic eruptions, violent earthquakes, and tsunamis often beset the country.
                 Fierce winter storms and flash floods alternate with severe summer droughts. When planning your trip, check which season is best to travel to your planned regions. 
                </p>
